==German==

===Etymology===
From the Middle High German ''[[strenge]]'', from Old High German ''[[strengi]]'' (''strong''), from Germanic ''*strangja-'' (''tight'', ''tense''), from the Proto-Indo-European ''*strenk-'' (''taut''); related to the Proto-Indo-European ''ster-'' (''stiff'').  Cf. the German [[Strenge]] and the English [[strong]].

===Pronunciation===
{{IPA|/ʃtʀɛŋ/}}
*:Hyphenation: '''streng''', ''comparative'' '''stren·ger''', ''superlative'' '''am strengs·ten'''

===Adjective===
'''streng'''
# severe, rigid, strict

#* '''1787''' [[CE]]: Johann Wolfgang von Goethe, ''Egmont''
#*: ''Ich sehe kein Mittel, weder '''strenges''' noch gelindes, dem Übel zu steuern.''
#*:: ''I see no means, neither '''severe''' nor mild, by which to stem the evil.''
# very much, strictly
#* '''1993''' [[CE]]: Die Ärzte, ''Lieber Tee''
#*: ''Da rauchen sie dann Haschisch ... aber dass ist '''streng''' geheim.''
#*:: ''There they smoke hashish ... but that is '''very much''' secret.''

====Usage notes====
*When '''streng''' is used with a verb in the sense of '''strongly''' / '''severely''', it can be translated into English using an adverb : ''dass ist '''streng''' geheim'' : ''that is '''strictly''' secret''.

